  "Question": "<p>The real numbers <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_217\"><math alttext=\"\\alpha,\\beta\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>\u03b1</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>\u03b2</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span> satisfy</p> <p><span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_218\"><math alttext=\"\\alpha^{3}-3\\alpha^{2}+5\\alpha-17=0\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mrow><mrow><msup><mi>\u03b1</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>\u2062</mo><msup><mi>\u03b1</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mrow><mo>+</mo><mrow><mn>5</mn><mo>\u2062</mo><mi>\u03b1</mi></mrow></mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>17</mn></mrow><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span> <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_219\"><math alttext=\"\\beta^{3}-3\\beta^{2}+5\\beta+11=0\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mrow><msup><mi>\u03b2</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>\u2062</mo><msup><mi>\u03b2</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mrow><mo>+</mo><mrow><mn>5</mn><mo>\u2062</mo><mi>\u03b2</mi></mrow><mo>+</mo><mn>11</mn></mrow><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span></p> <p>Find <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_220\"><math alttext=\"\\alpha+\\beta\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>\u03b1</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>\u03b2</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span></p> <ol> <li>Are the three roots of both cubic equations unique, or is there only one root? How can you prove it?</li> <li>What's the best approach to this problem?</li> </ol> <p>I tried using Vieta's formulas, where the sum of three roots of (1) and (2) are:</p> <p><span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_221\"><math alttext=\"\\alpha_{1}+\\alpha_{2}+\\alpha_{3}=3\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><msub><mi>\u03b1</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>\u03b1</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>\u03b1</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mrow><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span> <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_222\"><math alttext=\"\\beta_{1}+\\beta_{2}+\\beta_{3}=3\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><msub><mi>\u03b2</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>\u03b2</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>\u03b2</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mrow><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span></p> <p>Summing both,</p> <p><span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_223\"><math alttext=\"\\alpha_{1}+\\alpha_{2}+\\alpha_{3}+\\beta_{1}+\\beta_{2}+\\beta_{3}=6\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><msub><mi>\u03b1</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>\u03b1</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>\u03b1</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>\u03b2</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>\u03b2</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>\u03b2</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mrow><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span></p> <p>Assuming there is only one root for each of (1) and (2), we are done, but what if there isn't?</p>",
